Module 1, Task 4 Reflection
Margie Arnett, June 19

Prompt A
Before this module, I assumed my main challenge with AI was designing the right educational use case, prompt structure, and learner experience. Because I created the prototype for the Virtual Outpatient Clinic, I already understood that AI could support simulation, communication practice, and scalable learning. What this module complicated for me is the amount of time spent learning new tools that I may not use again. After reading and exploring, I understand that AI literacy is not just about using AI; it is also about deciding which tools are worth adopting and which add unnecessary burden.


Prompt B
I was surprised to learn that LLMs generate responses by predicting likely language patterns rather than truly “knowing” information the way a person does. This matters for my work because I create evaluation tools, student-facing instructions, summaries, and reports that need to be accurate, specific, and professionally responsible. If an AI produces a polished but incorrect statement, it could easily be mistaken for evidence-based language. In my role, I still need to check sources, review wording carefully, and make sure the output fits the context of IPE.


Prompt C
One task I perform regularly is summarizing student and facilitator feedback from IPE events. Based on what I learned, a specific AI mechanism that could impact me is pattern recognition across large amounts of text. AI could help identify common themes in Qualtrics comments, draft summaries, and suggest areas for improvement. A positive scenario is saving time during reporting. A cautionary scenario is that AI might overgeneralize feedback or miss a small but important concern. I would need to compare the summary against the actual data before using it.

